// 1. Async

// Think of async as saying:
// "This function will do some things that take time, like waiting for the oven to bake a cake. 
// Don’t expect it to finish instantly."

//In code:
async function bakeCake() {
    // This is an async function
}
// You must use async if you want to use await inside a function.

// 2. Await

// Think of await as saying:
// "Wait here until this thing is done before moving on."

// Real-life example:
await bakeCake();   // Wait until the cake is ready
eatCake();          // Only do this after the cake is baked

//In Playwright:

await page.goto('https://example.com'); // Wait until the page fully loads
await page.click('#login');             // Then click the login button

//Without await, your script would try to click before the page is ready, and it would fail.

//Super simple summary
//async → “This function works with things that take time.”
//await → “Wait here until this thing is finished.”

const { test } = require('@playwright/test');

test('Simple Async Await Example', async ({ page }) => {
    // Open a webpage and wait until it's fully loaded
    await page.goto('https://example.com');

    // Wait for a button to appear and then click it
    await page.click('text=More information');

    // Wait for some text to appear and then print it
    const content = await page.textContent('h1');
    console.log(content);
});

// Step by step:
// async ({ page }) → Marks the test function as asynchronous, so we can use await.
// await page.goto(...) → Waits for the page to load completely.
// await page.click(...) → Waits until the button is available and then clicks it.
// await page.textContent(...) → Waits until the text is retrieved before moving on.
// Without await, the script would try to click or read text before the page is ready, and it would fail.

// Why we need to make a function asynchronous (async)

// 1. Browser actions take time
// In Playwright, actions like page.goto(), page.click(), or page.fill() don’t happen instantly.
// They involve waiting for:
// The website to load
// Buttons or elements to appear
// Network responses
// If we wrote code synchronously, JS would try to do everything immediately without waiting, 
// and most actions would fail.
// 2. await only works inside async functions
// await is how we tell JavaScript: “Wait here until this task finishes.
// But JS only allows await inside functions marked with async.
// So if you want to wait for a page to load or a button to be clickable, you must mark the function as async.

// 3.Keeps code readable
// Without async/await, you’d have to use .then() chains, which get messy:

page.goto('https://example.com')
  .then(() => page.click('#login'))
  .then(() => page.fill('#username', 'Ashmita'));

//With async/await, it looks like normal top-to-bottom code:
await page.goto('https://example.com');
await page.click('#login');
await page.fill('#username', 'Ashmita');

// Perfect! Let’s use a real-life analogy:
// Async Function Analogy: Cooking Dinner

// Imagine you are cooking dinner:
// You start boiling water for pasta.
// While the water is heating, you chop vegetables.
// Once the water is ready, you cook the pasta.
// Then you mix pasta with veggies.

//How this maps to async and await:
//Reallife	                                          JavaScript/Playwright
//Boiling water	                                      page.goto('https://example.com')
//Waiting until it's ready	                          await page.goto(...)
//Chopping vegetables	                              Other JS code you can do in the meantime (non-blocking)
//Cooking pasta	                                      Next Playwright action (await page.click(...))

//async → “This function involves tasks that take time (like boiling water).”
//await → “Pause here until the task finishes before doing the next step.”

// Without marking it async, you can’t use await, and JS would try to “cook pasta” 
// before the water boils—obviously it fails!

//1. JavaScript is synchronous by default
//Yes, by default, JS runs top-to-bottom, line by line.
//But not all operations are synchronous. Some tasks, like network requests, timers, 
//or Playwright/browser actions, are asynchronous—they take time to complete.

//2. Why await is needed
//await pauses the function until a Promise resolves.
//A Promise is how JS represents something that will finish in the future, like loading a page.
//Without await, JS doesn’t wait for that Promise. It moves to the next line immediately.

//3. Why you still need async
// await can only be used inside an async function.
// If you try await in a normal function, JS throws an error:
// Marking the function async tells JS:
// "This function will contain asynchronous operations that may pause execution with await."

//4. Why it’s not just synchronous
// You cannot make Playwright actions synchronous because they rely on 
// external resources (browser, network, elements appearing).

// Even if JS is normally synchronous, these actions return Promises.
// JS can’t “pause” naturally without await or .then().

// So:
// Default JS → synchronous → works line by line, but cannot wait for a page to load naturally.
// Async/await → lets JS wait for async tasks like browser actions before moving on.

// ✅ Analogy:
// Without async/await → trying to eat pasta before water boils → disaster.
// With async/await → wait until water boils → then cook pasta → works perfectly.

//1. What is a Promise?
// A Promise in JavaScript is an object that represents a task that will finish in the future.
// It’s like a promise in real life: someone promises to give you something later.
// In JS, a Promise is something that will eventually:
// Resolve → the task finished successfully.
// Reject → the task failed.
// Pending → still in progress.

let pizzaOrder = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    let pizzaDelivered = true;

    if (pizzaDelivered) {
        resolve("Pizza is here!");
    } else {
        reject("Delivery failed!");
    }
});

// Using then/catch
pizzaOrder.then((message) => {
    console.log(message); // "Pizza is here!"
}).catch((error) => {
    console.log(error);
});

// 4. Why Promises matter in Playwright
// Actions like page.goto(), page.click() return Promises because:
// They take time (loading pages, waiting for elements).
// JS cannot pause by default, so it gives you a Promise as a placeholder.

const result = page.goto('https://example.com'); // result is a Promise

//To wait for it to finish, we use await:
await page.goto('https://example.com'); // Wait until the page is loaded

//✅ This ensures your next line of code only runs after the page is fully loaded.

// Summary
// Promise = a task that will finish in the future.
// States: pending → resolved → rejected.
// Use with async/await to make JS wait for async tasks like browser actions.


// 1. What they are
// async → Marks a function as asynchronous, allowing it to contain await.
// await → Pauses execution until a Promise resolves, ensuring actions complete before moving on.

// 2. Why they are needed in Playwright
// Playwright actions (like page.goto(), page.click(), page.fill()) 
// are asynchronous because they involve network requests, browser rendering, or waiting for elements.
// Without await, JS would continue immediately, and actions might fail.
// Without async, you cannot use await, so you cannot properly wait for these actions.

// 3. How they work
// async function → “This function contains tasks that take time.”
// await → “Pause here until this task finishes.”

// 1. What is a Promise in Playwright?
// A Promise is an object that represents a task that will finish in the future.
// Playwright actions like page.goto(), page.click(), or page.fill() are asynchronous and return a Promise.
// The Promise can be in one of three states:
// Pending → task is still running
// Resolved → task completed successfully
// Rejected → task failed

// 2. Why Playwright uses Promises
// Browser actions take time (loading pages, waiting for elements, network requests).
// JS cannot wait for them synchronously by default.
// Promises act as a placeholder for the result of the action.

// 4. Key points
// Every Playwright action that interacts with the browser returns a Promise.
// You must wait for it (using await) before performing the next action.
// Promises ensure that actions happen in the correct order and avoid errors.